176157	# Proxies
176158	
176159	  Beta This feature is in Beta.  We'd love to hear your feedback — please reach out via Slack or email us at support@modal.com. 
176160	
176161	You can securely connect with resources in your private network using a Modal Proxy. Proxies are a secure tunnel between Apps and exit nodes with static IPs. You can allow-list those static IPs in your network firewall, making sure that only traffic originating from these IP addresses is allowed into your network. 
176162	
176163	Proxies are unique and not shared between workspaces. All traffic between your Apps and the Proxy server is encrypted using WireGuard. 
176164	
176165	Modal Proxies are built on top of vprox, a Modal open-source project used to create highly available proxy servers using WireGuard. 
176166	
176167	## Creating a Proxy 
176168	
176169	  
176170	
176171	Proxies are available on the Team and Enterprise plans. Visit workspace settings to upgrade. 
176172	
176173	You can create Proxies in your workspace Settings page. Team Plan users can create one Proxy and Enterprise users three Proxies. Each Proxy can have a maximum of five static IP addresses. 
176174	
176175	Please reach out to support@modal.com if you need greater limits. 
176176	
176177	## Using a Proxy 
176178	
176179	 
176180	
176181	After a Proxy is online, add it to a Modal Function with the argument `proxy=Proxy.from_name("<your-proxy>")`. For example:  
176182	
176183	```
176184	import modal
176185	import subprocess
176186	
176187	app = modal.App(image=modal.Image.debian_slim().apt_install("curl"))
176188	
176189	@app.function(proxy=modal.Proxy.from_name("<your-proxy>"))
176190	def my_ip():
176191	    subprocess.run(["curl", "-s", "ifconfig.me"])
176192	
176193	@app.local_entrypoint()
176194	def main():
176195	    my_ip.remote()
176196	```
176197	 
176198	
176199	All network traffic from your Function will now use the Proxy as a tunnel. 
176200	
176201	The program above will always print the same IP address independent of where it runs in Modal’s infrastructure. If that same program were to run without a Proxy, it would print a different IP address depending on where it runs. 
176202	
176203	## Proxy performance 
176204	
176205	 
176206	
176207	All traffic that goes through a Proxy is encrypted by WireGuard. This adds latency to your Function’s networking. If you are experiencing networking issues with Proxies related to performance, first add more IP addresses to your Proxy (see Adding more IP addresses to a Proxy). 
176208	
176209	## Adding more IP addresses to a Proxy 
176210	
176211	 
176212	
176213	Proxies support up to five static IP addresses. Adding IP addresses improves throughput linearly. 
176214	
176215	You can add an IP address to your workspace in Settings > Proxies. Select the desired Proxy and add a new IP. 
176216	
176217	If a Proxy has multiple IPs, Modal will randomly pick one when running your Function. 
